    {
      "id": "9030d53f9693b7a76d5cfb8b1a901bf95fea4e81",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2014-07-29 14:30:27.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1\n\nSorry I broke that. Thanks for fixing it.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "4c619f75924d790615c6f2043b1b46e0a325225e",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2014-07-29 14:31:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nDoes this really need to be dependent on LU-1279?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "4044e5c95fbb32a5f948bb845036e6f27f652c75",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 141,
        "name": "Li Wei",
        "email": "wei.g.li@intel.com",
        "username": "liwei",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-07-29 14:41:22.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nJames, no, this does not really depend on the LU-1279 patch; it is only because I need a build that contains both.  By the way, could you have a look at the question in the third comment on this page, please?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e2196eac93e6dd9ef852ab56303cb18ebb032085",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2014-07-29 17:21:07.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nThe reason I moved from LIST_HEAD_INIT to INIT_HEAD_LIST was to make merging upstream easier and avoid conflicts on other potential platforms. Currently we have to do something like\n\nstatic struct list_head lu_sites = LIST_HEAD_INIT(lu_sites);\n\nto avoid the conflicts with the list handling in POSIX queue.h.The problem is the upstream maintainers would \nprefer if we did LIST_HEAD(lu_site) which is what would\nconflict. So to avoid that case I just port it to INIT_HEAD_LIST which doesn't have these issues.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "16ee9b478d268a50094e9f9fd7c4504dcc8b3968",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 284,
        "name": "Emoly Liu",
        "email": "emoly@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "liuying_emoly"
      },
      "date": "2014-08-01 09:45:11.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Code-Review+1",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "dbed7bd9829fbb7b3b90dadd5461f0ad5585bd86",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 125,
        "name": "James Simmons",
        "email": "jsimmons@infradead.org",
        "username": "jsimmons"
      },
      "date": "2014-08-04 21:48:47.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nCould you make LU-1279 dependent on this, ie reverse the dependency order.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "d92dd079ceb42a132cfa11a9ff5cbb3dcaf184be",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 141,
        "name": "Li Wei",
        "email": "wei.g.li@intel.com",
        "username": "liwei",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2014-08-05 01:32:40.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nJames, thanks for explaining the LIST_HEAD issue; I wasn't aware of the user space queue.h.  (By the way, queue.h is not POSIX but BSD.)  And, sure, let me rebase this and the LU-1257 patch to reverse the dependency.  Just curious: Does the unnecessary dependency break anything on your side?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e35ed0d2b18b900174e265d7e783d789699ca247",
      "author": {
